1 (C+B 4.1)

A random point (X, Y ) is distributed uniformly on the square with vertices (1, 1), (1, 1), (1, 1), (1, 1). That is the joint pdf is f (x, y) = \(\frac{1}{4}\) on the square. Determine the probabilities of the following events.

Note: Shade in the area that it is referring to

a

\(X^2+Y^2<1\) (Hint: think polar coordinates)

x1 <- seq(-1,1,0.001)

plot(c(-1,1), c(-1,1), type = "n", xlab="x", ylab = "pdf", asp = 1)
##add horizontal and vertical lines to get the box (abline)
abline(h = -1, v = 1, col = "blue")
abline(h = 1, v = -1, col="blue")
lines(x1, sqrt(1-x1^2), col="red")
lines(x1, -sqrt(1-x1^2), col="red")

b

\(2X-Y > 0\)

x1 <- seq(-1,1,0.001)

plot(c(-1,1), c(-1,1), type = "n", xlab="x", ylab = "pdf", asp = 1)
##add horizontal and vertical lines to get the box (abline)
abline(h = -1, v = 1, col = "blue")
abline(h = 1, v = -1, col="blue")
lines(x1, 2*x1, col="red")

c

\(|X+Y|<2\)

x1 <- seq(-1,1,0.001)

plot(c(-2,2), c(-2,2), type = "n", xlab="x", ylab = "pdf", asp = 1)
##add horizontal and vertical lines to get the box (abline)
abline(h = -1, v = 1, col = "blue")
abline(h = 1, v = -1, col="blue")
lines(x1, 2-x1, col="red")
lines(x1, -2-x1, col="red")

3 (C+B 4.4)

A pdf is defined by \[f(x,y) = \begin{cases} C(x+2y), & \mbox{if } 0<y<1 \text{ and } 0<x<2 \\ 0, & \mbox{ otherwise } \end{cases} \]

Remember: PDFs always have values between 0 and 1 because it is a probability

##need webgl=TRUE to initiate setup to get the graph inside the webpage

##you can zoom in and out, and twist the graph to explore it


##set up the data points - must be the same length
x1 <- seq(0,2,length = 1000)
x2 <- seq(0,1,length = 1000)
y <- 1/4 * (x1 + 2*x2)

##set up the matrix-like structure to plot
dat <- data.frame(x1, x2, y)
head(dat, 10) #print the first 10 rows of the dataframe dat
##             x1          x2           y
